Revise and extend macronutrient structure 

Amino acid 

Amino acids have unique side groups that result in differences in size, shape and electrical charge. Amino acids are linked together via peptide bonds, through condensation polymerisation. Note that protein folding is important for protein function.  

 

Carbohydrate structure 

 

Fat structure 

Saturated fatty acids have no double bonds, and occur primarily in animal products. Unsaturated fatty acids can be monounsaturated (1 double bond) or polyunsaturated (multiple double bonds).  

 

Fatty acids have a methyl end and an acid end. An omega-3 fatty acid can be written as 18:3 (18 Cs, 3 double bonds), w3, 6, 9, denoting double bonds after the 3rd, 6th and 9th carbons from the methyl end.  

 

Also note cis- and trans- double bonds: 

 

 

 

 

Describe the consequences of inadequate intake of macronutrients (protein-energy malnutrition) 

Carbohydrates 

Excess carbohydrates causes obesity, diabetes, nutritional deficits, dental caries, GI irritation, elevated triglycerides in plasma. Carbohydrate deficit causes tissue wasting and metabolic acidosis resulting from fat use for energy. 

 

Fats 

Excess fats causes obesity, cardiovascular disease. Fat deficit causes weight loss, tissue protein catabolism, problems controlling heat loss due to loss of subcutaneous fat, poor growth, risk of stroke, depression. Skin lesions due to insufficient essential fats 

 

Protein 

Excess protein causes obesity, enhanced calcium excretion and bone loss, high cholesterol levels in blood, kidney stones. Protein deficit causes weight loss and tissue wasting, growth stunting, anemia, edema, miscarriage, premature birth 

 

Briefly describe the concept of essential amino acids and essential fatty acids and the potential consequences of inadequate intake 

Essential amino acids cannot be synthesised by the body from new, and must be supplied through diet. Conditionally-essential amino acids are those that become indispensable under certain circumstances eg pregnancy, child growth, sickness etc. Non-essential amino acids can be synthesised by the body.  

 

Complete/high-quality proteins contain all essential amino acids in good quantity and correct ratio to maintain nitrogen balance. They are of an animal origin. Incomplete proteins lack one or more essential amino acids, and have a plant origin. Health impacts of protein-energy malnutrition include infections due to lack of antibodies, enlarged liver due to fatty infiltration, muscle wasting, fluid imbalances due to insufficient albumin, hair and tooth loss, ulcerative dermatitis, anemia, skin depigmentation, heart failure. 

 

Essential fatty acids, linoleic and alpha-linoleic, cannot be synthesised in the body and must be obtained from food. These are found in plant foods and used to build omega-3 and omega-6 fatty acids.  

 

Define vitamin and distinguish from mineral 

A vitamin is an organic compound that catalyses/supports a number of biochemical reactions in the body. 

A mineral is an inorganic compound which is a part of metabolic reactions or are used to provide structural support in body tissues.  

 

Define coenzyme and describe their role in enzymatic reactions 

Coenzymes are small organic molecules that bind temporarily to enzymes. The cofactor's presence is essential for the biological activity of the enzyme. The protein portion of the enzyme (apoenzyme) alone is inactive. The non-protein coenzyme can bind temporarily to this apoenzyme to provide a better fit between the active binding site and the target substrate.  

 

 

For example, B vitamins serve directly as coenzymes or are precursors to coenzymes (eg B9 folate and B12), assisting every cell in the human body.  

 

Briefly describe the consequences of common and important micronutrient deficiencies (iron, vitamin A, iodine, folate, B12, vitamin D, vitamin C) 

 

-Folate deficiency: 

Spina bifida is a congenital disorder caused by incomplete closing of embryonic neural tube, and can cause paralysis of varying degrees. Anencephaly can also occur, where the neural tube fails to close and causes a severely underdeveloped brain (baby born with only brainstem). Dietary folic acid can decrease the occurrence of neural tube defects. Megaloblastic anemia can also occur, where there is larger than normal RBCs with decreased RBC production. GIT problems, vascular disease etc can also occur. Folate deficiency is also a risk factor for neurodegenerative disorders. 

 

-B12 deficiency: 

B12 is only supplied by eating animal food. It is synthesised by anaerobic bacteria. It can cause megaloblastic anemia, or neurodegeneration.  

 

-C deficiency: 

Collagen structure is compromised resulting in scurvy (weakness, anemia, bruising, bleeding gums, loose teeth), impaired immunity 

 

-A deficiency: 

Night blindness, dry scaly skin, increased infection 

 

-D deficiency:  

Rickets (bone deformities) in children, bone softening in adults, poor muscle tone, joint pain, infection, cancer risk,  

 

 

-Iron deficiency 

Iron is used for O2 transport and storage. Iron deficiency leads to anemia, weakness, impaired immunity 

 

-Iodine deficiency 

Iodine is essential for the production of thyroid hormone, which regulates basic metabolic processes. Iodine deficiency leads to an enlarged thyroid, and hypothyroidism. This leads to stunted mental and physical growth and slow metabolism.
